{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515771"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:34:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12498"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12498"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.14,0.61,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111935"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5004"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8778"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111935"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents with a 6-month history of a red, scaly rash on her elbows, knees, and scalp. The rash is accompanied by intense itching and it is not improving with over-the-counter topical creams. She has no joint pain or swelling and or eye or mucosal symptoms. She is fit and well, not on any regular medications, and uses the Mirena intrauterine device for contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has silvery-white scales overlying erythematous plaques on the extensor surfaces of the her elbows and knees. The scalp is also involved. The natal cleft is spared. She has no open wound or cellulitic changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following signs are most likely to be found?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wickham\u0027s striae","Darier\u0027s sign","Nikolsky\u0027s sign","Auspitz sign","Hutchinson\u0027s sign"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with signs and symptoms indicating psoriasis. \u003Cstrong\u003EAuspitz sign\u003C/strong\u003E is most likely to be found in patients with psoriasis. This refers to the appearance of pinpoint bleeding after removing scales from the skin surface. It is a classic finding in patients with psoriasis, as it indicates the presence of dilated blood vessels within the papillary dermis. The mechanism behind the Auspitz sign is related to the increased angiogenesis and vascular permeability in psoriatic skin, which leads to the formation of tortuous, dilated blood vessels that are easily traumatised by removing the scales.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWickham\u0027s striae\u003C/strong\u003E refer to a lacy, white pattern seen on the surface of the skin in patients with lichen planus. The mechanism behind Wickham\u0027s striae is not fully understood, but it is thought to be related to the formation of a thickened stratum corneum and increased melanin in the basal layer of the epidermis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDarier\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E is a finding in patients with urticaria pigmentosa, where stroking or rubbing the skin causes wheals and itching. The mechanism behind Darier\u0027s sign is related to the release of histamine and other mediators from the mast cells, which causes vasodilation and increased permeability of blood vessels in the skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENikolsky\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E is found commonly in patients with pemphigus vulgaris, where gentle pressure on the skin causes separation of the epidermis. The mechanism behind Nikolsky\u0027s sign is related to the production of autoantibodies that target the desmosomal proteins in the epidermis, which leads to the breakdown of cell-cell adhesion and the formation of blisters. Nikolsky\u0027s sign can also be found in other conditions that involve blistering or detachment of the skin, such as Stevens-Johnson syndrome / Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis (TEN), pemphigus vulgaris, Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHutchinson\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E is a finding in patients with herpes zoster ophthalmicus, a viral infection caused by the varicella-zoster virus that affects the ophthalmic branch of the trigeminal nerve. This finding refers to the involvement of the tip of the nose in addition to the affected dermatome. The involvement of the tip of the nose is important as it suggests that the ophthalmic branch of the trigeminal nerve is affected, which can lead to serious ocular complications. The mechanism behind Hutchinson\u0027s sign involves the reactivation of the latent varicella-zoster virus within the sensory ganglia of the trigeminal nerve. This finding is crucial for prompt diagnosis and management of the infection, as ocular complications can occur and lead to vision loss if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Auspitz sign is a characteristic finding of psoriasis.","Auspitz sign refers to the appearance of pinpoint bleeding after removing scales from the skin surface."],"references":["Madke B, Nayak C. Eponymous signs in dermatology. Indian Dermatol Online J. 2012 Sep;3(3):159-65. doi: 10.4103/2229-5178.101810. Erratum in: Indian Dermatol Online J. 2013 Apr-Jun;4(2):164. PMID: 23189246; PMCID: PMC3505421.","Nair PA, Badri T. Psoriasis. 2022 Apr 6. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846344."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12498"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-22T08:42:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T08:45:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5004"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111935"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Lev